                                         WASHINGTON - The World Bank Group said its executive board approved on Tuesday a $1.15 billion development policy loan for Egypt to support the countryâ€™s economic reform programs. The loan is the last in a series of three annual loans totaling $3.15 billion issued from 2015 to 2017, the World Bank said in a statement. The $1.15 billion loan, which supports Egyptian economic reforms aimed at creating jobs, ensuring energy security, strengthening public finances and enhancing business competitiveness, includes financing contributions of $500 million from the World Bank Group, $500 million from the African Development Bank and $150 million from Britain.